---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="The Fibonacci Pipeline: How Much of Your Business Should an Agent Run? ~/stubborncoder"
  description="A simple ratio for integrating AI agents into enterprise operations: 60% deterministic code, 30% LLM reasoning, 10% human judgment."
  activeLink="writing"
>

<section class="post-hero">
  <div class="post-hero-bg"></div>
  <div class="post-hero-overlay"></div>
  <div class="post-hero-content wrap">
    <a href="/#writing" class="post-back reveal">&#8592; Back to writing</a>

    <div class="post-meta-top reveal">
      <span>April 2026</span>
      <span>&middot;</span>
      <span>6 min read</span>
    </div>

    <h1 class="reveal">The <span class="em">Fibonacci Pipeline</span></h1>

    <p class="post-subtitle reveal">
      How much of a business process should an agent actually run? The answer
      isn't 100%, and a rough 60/30/10 split is what I see working in practice.
    </p>

    <div class="post-tags-row reveal">
      <span class="post-tag post-tag--ember">AI Agents</span>
      <span class="post-tag post-tag--gold">Enterprise</span>
      <span class="post-tag">Pipeline Design</span>
      <span class="post-tag">Architecture</span>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<main class="wrap">
  <article class="article">

    <h2 class="reveal">How much should an agent run?</h2>

    <p class="reveal">
      Everyone's busy hyping what agents <em>can</em> do. Not many people are asking
      how much of a business process they <em>should</em> run.
    </p>

    <p class="reveal">
      Handing the whole thing to an agent is tempting. Read the data, make the call,
      act, done. Full autonomy. But finance teams don't hand over the keys because a
      demo looked cool. Operations won't let code approve purchase orders because it
      beat a benchmark. That's not how enterprise trust is built.
    </p>

    <p class="reveal">
      So the real question is how much. How much is code. How much is model. How
      much is human. There's a rough answer that holds up in practice.
    </p>

    <h2 class="reveal">60 / 30 / 10</h2>

    <div class="fibonacci-illustration reveal">
      <svg class="fib-svg" viewBox="0 0 400 250" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" aria-label="60 percent deterministic, 30 percent LLM, 10 percent human">

        <!-- Three squares in Fibonacci arrangement (tiled, sizes 240, 150, 90) -->
        <rect class="fib-box fib-box--code" x="5" y="5" width="240" height="240" rx="4" />
        <rect class="fib-box fib-box--llm" x="245" y="5" width="150" height="150" rx="4" />
        <rect class="fib-box fib-box--human" x="305" y="155" width="90" height="90" rx="3" />

        <!-- Fibonacci spiral: proper quarter arcs centered at inner corners -->
        <path class="fib-spiral-path"
              d="M 5 245 A 240 240 0 0 1 245 5 A 150 150 0 0 1 395 155 A 90 90 0 0 1 305 245"
              stroke-width="2.5"
              stroke-linecap="round"
              fill="none" />

        <!-- Labels -->
        <text class="fib-pct fib-pct--code" x="125" y="130" text-anchor="middle">60<tspan class="fib-pct-sym">%</tspan></text>
        <text class="fib-seg-label" x="125" y="154" text-anchor="middle">DETERMINISTIC</text>

        <text class="fib-pct fib-pct--llm" x="320" y="85" text-anchor="middle">30<tspan class="fib-pct-sym">%</tspan></text>
        <text class="fib-seg-label" x="320" y="107" text-anchor="middle">LLM</text>

        <text class="fib-pct fib-pct--human" x="350" y="205" text-anchor="middle">10<tspan class="fib-pct-sym">%</tspan></text>
        <text class="fib-seg-label fib-seg-label--small" x="350" y="222" text-anchor="middle">HUMAN</text>
      </svg>
    </div>

    <p class="reveal">
      <strong>60% deterministic.</strong> Code, rules, arithmetic, structured
      queries. The part that can't hallucinate because there's no model in it.
      Matching a PO to an invoice is math. Threshold checks are comparisons. Field
      validation is a regex. This is the backbone of the pipeline, it has to be
      solid.
    </p>

    <p class="reveal">
      <strong>30% LLM.</strong> Where only a model does the job. Classifying things
      that don't fit neatly into rules. Drafting text that needs to sound human.
      Judging materiality when the numbers alone don't tell the full story.
    </p>

    <p class="reveal">
      <strong>10% human.</strong> Approve, override, escalate. That 10% is where
      accountability lives. Someone looks at what the pipeline did, confirms it,
      hits go. Or stops it and says why.
    </p>

    <h2 class="reveal">Why this ratio works</h2>

    <p class="reveal">
      Each slice plays to its strength.
    </p>

    <p class="reveal">
      The deterministic 60% gives you <em>reliability</em>. Same input, same output,
      every time. No temperature, no prompt drift, no "it worked yesterday." When
      something breaks, you can trace it. When compliance asks what happened, you
      show them.
    </p>

    <p class="reveal">
      The LLM 30% gives you <em>intelligence</em>. These are the steps that used to
      need a person, not because they were hard, but because they needed context.
      "Is this price variance a mistake or a renegotiated contract?" "Escalate now
      or wait?" "How do I write this so the vendor actually fixes it?" Code can't
      answer that. Models can, if you scope them.
    </p>

    <p class="reveal">
      The human 10% gives you <em>trust</em>. Someone's in the loop, but only for
      the calls that carry weight. They're not reading every invoice or every
      email. They're reviewing the ones the agent flagged.
    </p>

    <blockquote class="reveal">
      <p>Nobody's removing humans from the process. You're giving them back the parts that actually need a person.</p>
    </blockquote>

    <h2 class="reveal">Latency is part of the design</h2>

    <p class="reveal">
      There's another reason the split works: speed. Deterministic steps run in
      milliseconds. A 3-way match is a DB query. A threshold check is a comparison.
      You can process thousands of these per second.
    </p>

    <p class="reveal">
      LLM calls are the bottleneck. Even fast models add seconds per call, and if
      your pipeline fires multiple calls per item (an assessment, an email, a
      routing decision), it adds up fast. In a pipeline chewing through thousands
      of items, the model steps are where latency lives.
    </p>

    <p class="reveal">
      That's why the ratio protects you. If 60% is deterministic, most of the work
      happens before the model gets involved. You only send the model what actually
      needs intelligence. Fewer calls, faster cycles.
    </p>

    <p class="reveal">
      And the models keep getting faster. Mercury 2, a diffusion-based model, runs
      at over 1,000 tokens per second with 1.7 second end-to-end latency. Claude
      Haiku 4.5 sits around 5 seconds. GPT-5 Mini at 4.5. For the kind of
      structured reasoning an enterprise pipeline needs (classify this issue, pick
      an action, draft a short email), a fast small model is more than enough. You
      don't need a frontier reasoning model to decide whether a price variance is
      the vendor's fault.
    </p>

    <p class="reveal">
      Keep the pipeline deterministic for throughput. Use a fast model for the 30%
      that needs brains. Full cycle runs in minutes, not hours, without a fortune
      in API calls.
    </p>

    <h2 class="reveal">When the ratio is off</h2>

    <p class="reveal">
      Too much LLM, not enough deterministic: inconsistency. Same invoice,
      different result on Tuesday than Monday. Your audit trail becomes "the model
      thought this was fine." Good luck with compliance.
    </p>

    <p class="reveal">
      Too much deterministic, not enough LLM: you're back where we were five years
      ago. A rules engine that breaks every time reality doesn't fit. Nobody can
      explain the edge cases because nobody built for them.
    </p>

    <p class="reveal">
      Too much human, not enough automation: you haven't automated anything. You've
      just added a dashboard to someone's already full day. The whole point was to
      free up the team for work that actually needs their brain.
    </p>

    <h2 class="reveal">How to think about it for your process</h2>

    <p class="reveal">
      Break the process into steps. For each step, ask: <em>does this need
      judgment or just execution?</em>
    </p>

    <p class="reveal">
      Execution: make it code. Test it. No model needed.
    </p>

    <p class="reveal">
      Judgment: then ask a second question: <em>routine or complex?</em> Routine
      (classify this, draft that, pick one of these) is the model's job. Complex
      (approving a &euro;500K exception, killing a vendor relationship) stays with
      a person.
    </p>

    <p class="reveal">
      Most processes land around 60/30/10 naturally. Not exactly, the numbers
      aren't the point. The principle is: <strong>build around code, use the
      model where it adds something code can't, keep humans on the calls that
      carry real weight.</strong>
    </p>

    <h2 class="reveal">Credit where it's due</h2>

    <p class="reveal">
      The Fibonacci Pipeline idea comes from
      <a href="https://www.skool.com/ai-automation-society/about" target="_blank" class="inline-link">Nate Herk</a>
      and his AI Automation Society community. Framing agents as pieces of a
      larger flow, not replacements for it, clicked for me immediately. It's how
      I think about every system I build for enterprise clients now.
    </p>

    <div class="article-footer reveal">
      <div class="article-footer-label">Connect</div>
      <div class="resource-links">
        <a href="https://linkedin.com/in/daviddiaztrapero" target="_blank" class="original-link">LinkedIn &#8594;</a>
        <a href="https://www.skool.com/ai-automation-society/about" target="_blank" class="original-link">AI Automation Society &#8594;</a>
      </div>
    </div>

  </article>

  <section class="more-posts">
    <div class="more-posts-title">More writing</div>
    <a href="/blog/invoice-verification-agent" class="more-row">
      <span class="more-date">2026.04</span>
      <span class="more-title">Let AP Clerks Do the Work That Needs a Human</span>
      <span class="more-src">CFO Living Examples, Part 2</span>
    </a>
    <a href="/blog/ar-collections-agent" class="more-row">
      <span class="more-date">2026.04</span>
      <span class="more-title">Your AR Team Just Got an Agent That Never Sleeps</span>
      <span class="more-src">CFO Living Examples, Part 1</span>
    </a>
    <a href="/blog/multimodal-embeddings" class="more-row">
      <span class="more-date">2026.04</span>
      <span class="more-title">Multimodal Embeddings: One Model, One Vector Space</span>
      <span class="more-src">LinkedIn</span>
    </a>
  </section>
</main>

</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .post-hero { position: relative; padding: 10rem 0 4rem; overflow: hidden; }
  .post-hero-bg { position: absolute; inset: 0; background: url('https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1509228468518-180dd4864904?w=1920&q=80') center/cover no-repeat; filter: blur(8px) saturate(0.3) brightness(0.25); transform: scale(1.05); transition: filter var(--ease); }
  :global([data-theme="light"]) .post-hero-bg { filter: blur(8px) saturate(0.35) brightness(1.1); }
  .post-hero-overlay { position: absolute; inset: 0; background: var(--hero-overlay); mask-image: linear-gradient(to bottom, rgba(0,0,0,0.3) 0%, rgba(0,0,0,1) 70%); -webkit-mask-image: linear-gradient(to bottom, rgba(0,0,0,0.3) 0%, rgba(0,0,0,1) 70%); }
  .post-hero-content { position: relative; z-index: 2; max-width: 720px; }
  .post-back { font-size: 0.75rem; color: var(--text-lo); display: inline-flex; align-items: center; gap: 6px; margin-bottom: 2rem; transition: color 0.2s; text-decoration: none; }
  .post-back:hover { color: var(--ember); }
  .post-meta-top { display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 1rem; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; font-size: 0.72rem; color: var(--text-lo); flex-wrap: wrap; }
  .post-hero h1 { font-family: 'Libre Baskerville', serif; font-size: clamp(2rem, 4.5vw, 3rem); font-weight: 400; line-height: 1.25; color: var(--text-hi); letter-spacing: -0.02em; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; }
  .post-hero h1 .em { color: var(--ember); font-style: italic; }
  .post-subtitle { font-size: 1rem; color: var(--text); max-width: 560px; line-height: 1.8; }
  .post-tags-row { display: flex; gap: 0.5rem; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-top: 1.5rem; }
  .post-tag { font-size: 0.65rem; padding: 3px 8px; border-radius: 4px; border: 1px solid var(--border); color: var(--text-lo); }
  .post-tag--ember { color: var(--ember); border-color: var(--ember-border); background: var(--ember-glow); }
  .post-tag--gold { color: var(--gold); border-color: rgba(212,166,69,0.2); background: var(--gold-dim); }

  .article { max-width: 720px; padding: 4rem 0 6rem; }
  .article h2 { font-family: 'Libre Baskerville', serif; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 400; color: var(--text-hi); margin-top: 3rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; padding-top: 2rem; border-top: 1px solid var(--border); }
  .article h2:first-child { border-top: none; padding-top: 0; margin-top: 0; }
  .article p { font-family: 'Libre Baskerville', serif; font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.9; color: var(--text); margin-bottom: 1.25rem; }
  .article strong { color: var(--text-hi); font-weight: 600; }
  .article em { color: var(--ember); font-style: italic; }
  .article blockquote { border-left: 3px solid var(--blockquote-border); background: var(--blockquote-bg); padding: 1.25rem 1.5rem; margin: 2rem 0; border-radius: 0 8px 8px 0; }
  .article blockquote p { font-style: italic; color: var(--text-hi); margin-bottom: 0; font-size: 0.92rem; }

  .fibonacci-illustration { margin: 2.5rem 0; display: flex; justify-content: center; }
  .fib-svg { width: 100%; max-width: 560px; }

  /* Square fills */
  .fib-box { fill-opacity: 0.1; stroke-width: 1.5; }
  .fib-box--code { fill: var(--ash); stroke: var(--ash); }
  .fib-box--llm { fill: var(--ember); stroke: var(--ember); }
  .fib-box--human { fill: var(--gold); stroke: var(--gold); }

  /* Labels */
  .fib-pct {
    font-family: 'Iosevka', monospace;
    font-size: 36px;
    font-weight: 600;
  }
  .fib-pct--code { fill: var(--ash); }
  .fib-pct--llm { fill: var(--ember); }
  .fib-pct--human { fill: var(--gold); }
  .fib-pct-sym {
    font-size: 18px;
    opacity: 0.6;
  }

  .fib-seg-label {
    font-family: 'Iosevka', monospace;
    font-size: 11px;
    letter-spacing: 0.2em;
    fill: var(--text-hi);
    font-weight: 500;
  }
  .fib-seg-label--small { font-size: 9px; letter-spacing: 0.15em; }

  /* Fibonacci spiral overlay */
  .fib-spiral-path {
    stroke: var(--ember);
    stroke-dasharray: 1400;
    stroke-dashoffset: 1400;
    animation: fib-spiral-draw 2.5s cubic-bezier(0.22, 1, 0.36, 1) forwards;
    animation-delay: 0.4s;
    opacity: 0.9;
  }
  @keyframes fib-spiral-draw { to { stroke-dashoffset: 0; } }

  .inline-link { color: var(--ember); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 3px; transition: color 0.2s; }
  .inline-link:hover { color: var(--gold); }

  .article-footer { border-top: 1px solid var(--border); padding-top: 2.5rem; margin-top: 3rem; }
  .article-footer-label { font-size: 0.68rem; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.1em; color: var(--text-lo); margin-bottom: 1rem; }
  .resource-links { display: flex; gap: 0.75rem; flex-wrap: wrap; }
  .original-link { display: inline-flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px; font-size: 0.82rem; color: var(--text-hi); padding: 0.65rem 1.1rem; border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 8px; transition: all 0.2s; text-decoration: none; }
  .original-link:hover { border-color: var(--ember-border); color: var(--ember); }

  .more-posts { padding: 4rem 0; border-top: 1px solid var(--border); }
  .more-posts-title { font-size: 0.72rem; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.1em; color: var(--text-lo); margin-bottom: 1.5rem; }
  .more-row { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 90px 1fr auto; gap: 1.5rem; align-items: baseline; padding: 1.25rem 0; border-top: 1px solid var(--border); cursor: pointer; transition: all 0.2s; text-decoration: none; }
  .more-row:hover { padding-left: 0.75rem; }
  .more-row:hover .more-title { color: var(--ember); }
  .more-date { font-size: 0.72rem; color: var(--text-lo); font-variant-numeric: tabular-nums; }
  .more-title { font-size: 0.85rem; color: var(--text-hi); transition: color 0.2s; }
  .more-src { font-size: 0.65rem; color: var(--text-lo); text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.06em; }

  @media (max-width: 768px) { .more-row { grid-template-columns: 1fr; gap: 0.3rem; } .post-hero { padding: 8rem 0 3rem; } .resource-links { flex-direction: column; } }
</style>
